00:16:17.310 --> 00:16:20.046 align:middle
Last year we introduced
Metal at WWDC as a way

00:16:20.046 --> 00:16:23.683 align:middle
to accelerate graphics in
high-performance games.

00:16:23.683 --> 00:16:26.219 align:middle
It takes the overhead
out of OpenGL,

00:16:26.219 --> 00:16:28.120 align:middle
providing a high-performance API

00:16:28.120 --> 00:16:30.423 align:middle
that gives the game
direct access to the power

00:16:30.423 --> 00:16:32.425 align:middle
of the underlying
graphics hardware.

00:16:32.425 --> 00:16:36.028 align:middle
Well, this year we are
bringing Metal to the Mac.

00:16:36.028 --> 00:16:38.397 align:middle
And we are doing more than that.

00:16:38.397 --> 00:16:41.567 align:middle
Because we are taking the
graphic stacks on which apps

00:16:41.567 --> 00:16:44.470 align:middle
on OS X are built, Core
Animation and Core Graphics,

00:16:44.470 --> 00:16:48.908 align:middle
and moving them from OpenGL to
run natively on top of Metal,

00:16:48.908 --> 00:16:50.810 align:middle
making everything you do faster.

00:16:50.810 --> 00:16:53.145 align:middle
We are seeing 50
percent improvements

00:16:53.145 --> 00:16:56.482 align:middle
in rendering performance
and a 40 percent reduction

00:16:56.482 --> 00:16:59.118 align:middle
in the amount of CPU
necessary to do graphics.

00:16:59.118 --> 00:17:01.654 align:middle
That means improved performance
for your applications


WEBVTT
